ðŸš€ Trapping Rainwater â€“ All Solutions (C++)
 link: https://leetcode.com/problems/trapping-rain-water/submissions/1681161133/
ðŸ”¹ Solution 1: Brute Force Approach
Intuition:

Har index pe water trapped = minimum of (max on left, max on right) â€“ height[i]

Left aur Right max ke liye har index pe loop chalana padega â†’ O(NÂ²)

Code:
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int trapBrute(vector<int>& height) {
    int n = height.size();
    int water = 0;

    // Iterate through each index
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        int leftMax = 0, rightMax = 0;

        // find left max
        for (int j = i; j >= 0; j--) {
            leftMax = max(leftMax, height[j]);
        }

        // find right max
        for (int j = i; j < n; j++) {
            rightMax = max(rightMax, height[j]);
        }

        // trapped water = min(leftMax, rightMax) - current height
        water += min(leftMax, rightMax) - height[i];
    }
    return water;
}

int main() {
    vector<int> arr = {0,1,0,2,1,0,1,3,2,1,2,1};
    cout << "Brute Force: " << trapBrute(arr) << endl; // Output: 6
}


â± Time Complexity: O(NÂ²)
ðŸ’¾ Space Complexity: O(1)

ðŸ”¹ Solution 2: Prefixâ€“Suffix (Better Approach)
Intuition:

Left max aur Right max baar-baar calculate karne ki jagah prefix aur suffix arrays precompute kar lo.

prefix[i] = max height from [0â€¦i]

suffix[i] = max height from [iâ€¦n-1]

Code:
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int trapPrefixSuffix(vector<int>& height) {
    int n = height.size();
    if (n == 0) return 0;

    vector<int> prefix(n), suffix(n);

    // Build prefix max
    prefix[0] = height[0];
    for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
        prefix[i] = max(prefix[i - 1], height[i]);
    }

    // Build suffix max
    suffix[n - 1] = height[n - 1];
    for (int i = n - 2; i >= 0; i--) {
        suffix[i] = max(suffix[i + 1], height[i]);
    }

    // Calculate trapped water
    int water = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        water += min(prefix[i], suffix[i]) - height[i];
    }

    return water;
}

int main() {
    vector<int> arr = {4,2,0,3,2,5};
    cout << "Prefix-Suffix: " << trapPrefixSuffix(arr) << endl; // Output: 9
}


â± Time Complexity: O(N)
ðŸ’¾ Space Complexity: O(N) (for prefix & suffix arrays)

ðŸ”¹ Solution 3: Two Pointer Approach (Optimal)
Intuition:

Left aur Right dono side se ek-saath traverse karte hain.

Maintain leftMax aur rightMax.

Jo side chhoti hai usko move karte hain â†’ kyunki water hamesha shorter boundary pe depend karega.

Dry Run Example [0,1,0,2,1,0,1,3,2,1,2,1]:

Start: left=0, right=11, leftMax=0, rightMax=0

Compare height[left] aur height[right]

Move smaller side, update max, aur water add karo.

At the end total = 6

Code:
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int trapTwoPointer(vector<int>& height) {
    int n = height.size();
    int left = 0, right = n - 1;
    int leftMax = 0, rightMax = 0, water = 0;

    while (left < right) {
        // Update leftMax and rightMax
        leftMax = max(leftMax, height[left]);
        rightMax = max(rightMax, height[right]);

        // Decide which side to process
        if (leftMax <= rightMax) {
            water += leftMax - height[left];
            left++;
        } else {
            water += rightMax - height[right];
            right--;
        }
    }
    return water;
}

int main() {
    vector<int> arr = {0,1,0,2,1,0,1,3,2,1,2,1};
    cout << "Two Pointer: " << trapTwoPointer(arr) << endl; // Output: 6
}


â± Time Complexity: O(N)
ðŸ’¾ Space Complexity: O(1)

ðŸ“Œ Final Notes for Interview

Brute Force â€“ start with this (shows basic idea).

Prefix-Suffix â€“ show improvement with extra space.

Two Pointer â€“ explain intuition clearly â†’ shorter side decides trapped water.
